qMetaDef.title: Diversity Workforce Analysis
qMetaDef.description: A recent Gallup study have found that gender-diverse business units are highly engaged, and financial performance improves dramatically.

style.text:
**D****iversity**  has been proven vital to any workplace. Not just because it's a laudable goal; it simply makes bottom\-line business sense. Based in this premise we would like to understand gender\-diversity in our company. We can see that 63.2% of the workforce are males while just around 36% are females.

If we break down these company percentages by country and by job role, we can observe how gender diversity works across geographies and positions. The bars in the charts below represent the ratio of women by country and job role. We can note that the ratio of females to males does not reach the 50% for any of the countries nor job roles.

On average, females lag behind males when we compare their overall salaries.  The same behavior is observed  for each management role. However, among Senior Managers, there is a big difference in compensation. Men make a little over $3K more than their female counterparts.^[
Women are not as well represented in the higher paying job groups \(management positions\). As we can see in the Female ratio by Management role bar chart, women represent 29,2% and 34,9% for the two more popular management roles which is less than the ratio of women in contributor roles \(general workers\) 36.5%.
\_\_\_\_
%[_It's important to note that there is a very small number of senior managers in the company, sample data may not be conclusive for that group._](2)
